segments.text: hitchhike place south of Dallas.
Well I'll take you.
He had a driver.
I don't know who it was but I kind of, I don't know what he did but it didn't sound, anyway.
You just never knew, but it usually took about five hours.
We'd leave about eight or nine in the morning, and we would be lucky to be back by noon, one o'clock, something.
Did you ever have any bad Aggie hitchhiking experience?
None.
All right, you're giving the same answer everybody else has.
You know, I even got a ride one night at 1 a.m. in Odessa, Texas, coming out here.
A guy had just gotten married with his wife in a brand new car, gave two of us a ride at 1 a.m.
Boy, that day is long gone.
Isn't it?
And see, today's students, they can't believe that, that you hitchhiked and it was safe.
The only things I, and that's one of my standard questions about hitchhiking.
Occasionally somebody will say the guy was drinking too much or was driving too fast.
One guy, he was in a hurry to get to Houston because his wife or his girlfriend was playing around with somebody else and he was going down there to beat that guy up, but he let them out early.
and nobody's ever mentioned any wreck or accident or nothing like that.
All right, back to the daily routine.
Class at 8 o'clock.
What did you do between classes if you had an hour to spare without a class?
It varied.
A lot of guys would study.
I never seemed to do that.
I went to the MSC a lot, or I'd go back to the dorm room.
took care of whatever.
You had to get your laundry out and ready to go or you needed just your personal stuff, haircut, whatever.
I didn't have very many hours off.
When you're taking 20 hours, you don't have many hours off.
You marched to all three meals, and it was in Duncan?
No.
Or Sabeasa?
Sabeasa your freshman year.
And then when we moved to the new area, it was called, and then it was over at Duncan.
In the MSC, where did you spend any time?
Well, it was a little different than it is now.
The original part up front is about the same, but as you were going what would be east,
The post office was right in that front corner up there.
And then you went down that long ramp and there was a snack bar, kind of a coffee shop.
And none of the stuff that's in the back, all the bookstores and all that was there.
And I used to go get something to eat, whatever treat, if I could afford to have something.
as opposed to eating at Dunkin'.
If you had an afternoon with a couple of hours free, what did you do with free time in the afternoon?
I never remember.
I remember having, you know, like the cut for the bonfire.
I don't know how we didn't kill ourselves.
Raining, slippery, carrying those logs out of there.
And I remember I used to have to do it on Saturday and Sunday, I think it was, because I didn't have any free time.
About how long did the bonfire work?
I think we started in October, as I recall.
Do you remember what direction from the campus?
You know, I've often thought about that.
Where were those trees we were cutting down?
They put us on trucks and cars and took us out there.
And you all were cutting them down?
Well, I wasn't.
but we were hauling them out.
What were they using to cut them with then?
Axes.
Okay, that's what I thought.
Do you remember anybody getting hurt?
I never remember anybody getting hurt.
Not to say they didn't.
Usually there wasn't any.
And Bonfire was then held on the drill field.
It was in the drill field, and that was one of the big tragedies while I was there, was those two Aggie graduates who were Navy pilots
that buzzed the bonfire and dove and the wings came off and they bore a hole right there on Welborn Road.
Do you remember any pranks or anything?
Somebody from Texas came over and tried to drop something on it one time, but we didn't have, you know, there was always rumors.
They're on their way to burn the bonfire.
All right, in the dining hall, any good bull there?
Any pranks that you or anybody else tried in the dining hall?
Oh, well, you know, we tried to always, of course, freshmen couldn't have dessert.
We were always trying to steal it.
Did y'all have cush questions?
Yep.
Do you remember any of them?
No, I mean, I don't remember what they were.
One that you can pass on is my favorite.
How many stars are there in the Texas flag?
One as far as I know.
No, there's two.
There's one on each side.
And if you say two, you say, no, it's one.
It goes through both ways.
So there is no credit.
Let's see.
In class, how did you and your buddies behave?
Oh, I think we were, everybody there was really very respectful, a lot more than even high school.
In those days, high school was perfectly orderly.
I think the people that were at A&M when I was there felt one, they were fortunate to be there, and two, they needed that degree.
And we buckled down.
We didn't.
If you wanted to get away for an hour or something to kind of go and
just be by yourself, not be interrupted, where would you have gone?
Probably my dorm room.
Maybe I was, I guess there were some guys down there that were taking the degree programs that didn't require the number of hours or whatever.
And I know a lot of them went down to, there was some kind of quarry south of, they used to go down there and go swimming.
I never had the opportunity to do that.
Nobody yet remembers where it was, but they all remember going.
It was somewhere south Wellborn Road, and then a little west toward the river.
And they go down there in Skinny Dip.
Nobody has described anything going on that was really bad.
Yep, drink some beer, but nobody's ever talked about anything with a bunch of women or anything like that.
You know, I never had, I never, ever,
Had my wife come to A&M.
I never had the money.
I never went to a dance at A&M.
Really?
No.
All right.
Do you remember your freshman year?
We had the cotton ball.
It was a big dance.
But wait.
Let's go back to football season.
There was a court trip to either Dallas or Fort Worth.
We had my freshman year, and I've got pictures of that.
We went to Fort Worth for the TCU game, and we went to Houston.
Wait a minute.
Yeah, that's right.
Yeah, Houston.
Either Houston or Austin.
Well, I think it was Houston that year.
Okay.
And then the following year we went to Dallas and Austin.
All right.
When up there that freshman year, did you bring her down to the game?
Well, there were so many Aggies dating so many Tessies that they had a bus that brought them all down right to the stadium.
Mm-hmm.
Now, who paid for that bus?
She did.
She did?
And then did y'all go back to Dentonville?
No, we spent, we were lucky.
Her roommate was from Fort Worth.
And we had, one of the guys in the outfit was from Fort Worth, obviously.
We all, four or five of us stayed with him.
And we did go out.
I forget where we went that Saturday night.
And then she went back and we went back.
And do you remember any, on that court trip or any others, do you remember anything going on that really shouldn't have?
Not that I know of.
Pretty tame in those days by today's standards.
Well, oh yeah.
That's the only time she ever came
to a court trip game.
Even in Dallas, I don't think that would have been in my sophomore year for whatever reason.
She wasn't there.
And, you know, we just went up and marched, went to the game, and then I went back.
Now, did you tell her about the Aggie tradition after Aggies score a touchdown?
We still do that even on the TV games, right today.
And our kids think we're crazy.
And, all right, where did you spend the night?
Did you have up there?
Well, somebody in my freshman outfit was from Fort Worth, and we stayed at his house.
And there would be dozens?
Well, there were, I think, four or five of us there.
Did you hitchhike up there and back, probably?
Oh, yeah.
Or somebody had a car.
Very few people had cars, but I think a few of them did, and I think we got a ride up there.
I remember going to Houston the first time.
We went on the train.
The Owl, or whatever it was called, went through there.
We went on the train.
How did, on a court trip, how did you feel as you were wearing that uniform?
Oh, proud as a peacock.
Why?
I don't know.
But I, by golly, we were different.
As a person who did not go to A&M as an undergraduate, I think that's part of the building of the spirit.
It is that being a part of the group.
It is unbelievable.
Oh, yes, yes.
Was there a fish day in your time?
I don't think there was.
I don't remember that.
Back in the earlier, before the war, there was a fish day where for one day the fish ran everything.
Oh, yeah, that wasn't, no, that wasn't.
All right, you came home Christmas.
I came home Christmas, and in those days, of course, finals were not until after Christmas.
I came home Christmas, and then right after New Year's we went back.
You had a couple of days off at Thanksgiving, of course, but I stayed for the game and didn't come home.
Wouldn't have anyway because I had no way to get home that short.
And then you had Easter, which was about close to a week or four or five days, and I came home.
My sophomore year for Easter, as I recall.
I don't think I ever came home for Thanksgiving.
During that first year or maybe two years, how did you and your family communicate?
By letter.
How often?
About once a week.
It was unheard of to make long-distance calls.
And if you got a long-distance call, and I got one or two, they would call to the MSC.
And then they'd send a runner over to your dorm, and you'd call back.
And where was the telephone in your dorm?
You know, there was one, but I don't know where it was.
It was somewhere down at the end of the hallway, I think.
No, they had it in the day room.
Oh, okay.
And I think that was true in all the dorms.
I never got a call there.
The two I got, I had to go to the MSC.
Then at the end of your freshman year, what did you feel like when you went through final review?
Oh, I thought, man, I made it.
I made it.
That's the greatest feeling in the world.
I survived, and I'm better than all those people that quit.
And were you then pleased, proud that you had not dropped out?
That's right.
I have accomplished something.
You come home that summer?
Mm-hmm.
What did you do?
I had worked the previous summer.
I worked, I guess that summer I worked for Southern Union Gas as a draftsman here.
And did you ever think about changing your major?
No.
And how did you, why did you pick that major in the first place?
Well, as I said, my dad was with the General Electric Company.
He had not had
the ability and the privilege of going to college.
And he said, of course, in those days, the General Electric Company revolved around electrical engineers.
And that was the one thing, which is kind of irony, he said, you need to get a degree.
I had decided I wanted to be an electrician.
He said, you need to get a degree, and you need to go to work for the General Electric Company.
They take care of you.
So that's what you thought you were going to be, as a corporate engineer?
I graduated in 55.
I had to get a deferment.
In those days, you had to go in, and I was scheduled to report to pre-flight, and I got a deferment.
My wife was teaching school to get a master's degree.
During graduate school, I said, you know, I'm not sure that I really like this big company corporate deal, and I wanted to kind of look around, but I never really got into it.
And then all of a sudden, I've graduated with a master's degree, and GE had made me an offer the first time,
They raised it, and my dad says, you need to take that.
Of course, at that point, Rick, our oldest son, was born the night I got my degree, my master's degree.
In fact, I had to ride in my cap and gown on a bicycle to graduation because I'd been banned from the campus.
I had this old clunker of a car.
And I used to sell TV antennas.
I ran a little want ad in the Bryan Eagle.
And to make a little extra money, in those days, there was a station in Waco and one in Houston.
And you could put up a big 30, 40 foot telescopic mast and an antenna and a rotor.
And I used to advertise and sell those installed.
And I had this old car with a rack on top and carry that stuff.
And, of course, I was out doing, trying to do that.
And then I pull up and park in the faculty lot behind the EE building.
And after I got about three tickets, why, you can't drive on campus anymore.
Back to undergraduate days.
the main facilities for you and all your buddies, there was the MSC.
Did you encounter Wayne Stark?
Did you get acquainted with him?
What kind of guy was he?
I don't, I mean, just as a student, great guy as far as I could tell.
Superb.
Yeah.
Were you involved in any major extracurricular group?
No, the only thing I was in, what is it, Phi Eta Sigma and Tau Beta Pi.
And Ross volunteers, and I, you know, that was it.
As far as you know, how did one become an RV?
Did you?
In those days, one day they called me over and it was the academic building.
All those deals.
I didn't know that much about the RVs, in fact.
No, like you didn't go say, I want to be considered.
You didn't submit an... No.
They said, you've been selected.
And as far as you know, people were selected on the basis of...
I guess merit.
I don't know how they were selected.
And you were doing well also in your corps.
Yeah, yeah.
And in those days how many juniors were selected for Army?
What were they?
There were three companies, three companies and in each company four times
about 40, there must have been about 120.
So out of that, probably 60% of them were juniors.
Do you have any idea whether there was any favoritism?
I have no idea.
I've never heard of anybody who thought there was.
I don't know how we were selected.
So if there was some secret backroom deal on it, I wasn't aware of it.
Did you ever go to the Quack Shack?
Were you ever sick?
No, but it was right there across from Walton.
They had that old
old military 4x4 ambulance.
I went over there one time and I had a sore throat and you know the stories about it were unbelievable and they had that old guy that was a doctor, remember that?
But I never had to go there.
I never really got sick of any of them under the cold.
Alright, Guyon Hall.
Oh yeah, used to go to Guyon.
That was, I guess that was the only thing
That and go downtown to the movie in downtown Bryan.
When we were there for the Iowa State game, Marilyn and I drove downtown.
Those theaters are kind of there, but they're not theaters anymore.
In fact, old Tom Dollahyte and I would, one of us would scale the back wall up into the window in the back, slip in, go down, and open that back door for four or five of us to get in.
And to go in?
And it was only a dime to go, but we didn't have a dime.
Now what kind of pranks did Aggies do during a guy in the movie?
None while I was there.
Oh, I thought you all yelled and hooted.
Well, nothing.
Not that I remember.
Because sometimes in other years then they would make noise apparently and yell and shout.
Along with the movie?
Yeah, along with the movie.
Did you go much to the campus theater?
Over there, yeah.

Yeah, in fact, my roommate, who didn't, he couldn't get a pass at physical, so he had to get transferred to tech after our sophomore year, George D. Sang, which the architect, Carol Doble, and George, our freshman year, that was their project to do, in architecture, to do one of these little models of a remodeling, and that
George and I grew up together and I had the top bunk and he had the bottom bunk and he was working on that model and he just finished it.
Uh oh.
And he had it on the footlocker at the end of the bed.
Uh oh.
And I crawl up, my clothes in the top, take my shoes off, throw them over the end and right down through the model.
Were there any, while you were there, any special groups or speakers or campus visitors you remember in either G. Raleigh or Guyon?
Well, you got to realize that, let's see, G. Raleigh was built
the basketball arena, G. Raleigh wasn't there.
Is that right?
Okay.
I forgot.
We had the old red brick building right there.
What was that called?
Oh, boy.
You know where the bat is?
Yeah, yeah.
That's where we went to basketball.
Okay.
Were there any celebrity visitors, speakers, performers?
Well, this was when I was in graduate school, I guess.
I remember Marilyn and I went over to Guy and then, oh, one of the movie stars or something, a speaker.
And the big bands were no longer coming to the- We had a couple of them my freshman year.
They played, one of them played at the, I remember the Grove, for one of the, I think the Cotton Ball.
But I didn't go.
Religious activities on the campus.
Did you attend any?
The Episcopal Church there on South Gate is still there.
Yeah, yeah.
About how many students went over there, do you?
Twenty, twenty-five, something like that.
Do you remember Religious Emphasis Week in the spring?
No.
Okay.
Here's an important question.
Describe the student body in general.
Well, I think the most important word is close-knit.
I think the longer they were there, if you finished primarily that first semester, if you lasted until January, it almost became like a religion and like a family.
What made it so?
Because everybody endured the same thing.
And I think while there was a lot of different backgrounds and there was a certain amount of spread, let's say, in the economic ladder, there wasn't all that much.
There was a few kids there that had money, maybe from a couple of oil families or a lot of ranching families, but you'd never know it.
They may have had a car.
Everybody was pretty close-knit.
I don't think that was true at other universities.
I think you're right.
Geographically, where were they from?
Well, most of them, I'd say 90 percent of them were from Texas.
Okay.
But then within Texas, were there?
Primarily from central, south, east Texas.
There weren't that many from west Texas.
Was there both town and country?
Yes, obviously, but I can't tell you whether there was more rural when there were city or not.
But I would say it would be pretty hard not to have a predominance of major metropolitan areas.
I'm guessing, I don't know.
And were there Catholic and Protestant and Jewish?
A close friend of mine was Jewish, and his father was the merchant there in Junction, Texas, had the little clothing store.
Didn't, I mean...
But El Paso is that way.
We've got a diverse community and nobody even thinks about that.
That's right.
Did it matter?
No.
Why didn't it?
I don't know.
It didn't matter here to me so it didn't matter to me down there.
I think it's because everybody went through the same experience.
That's right.
In that era did almost everybody have a nickname or was it beginning to pass?
I don't remember too many of them having nicknames.
In fact, I had a nickname and got rid of it down there.
Alright, let's go back to athletics.
Describe the routine for an Aggie on a home football weekend.
That was a great experience.
The weekend started when?
We had yell practice.
Where?
At the Grove.
I was there the night Bear Bryant got off the train.
Oh, describe that.
That is one of my biggest experiences at A&M.
It was like March or April, as I recall, which was late.
And I remember we all went to the Grove.
I was there when Ray George.
When I got there, Ray George had come from Southern Cal or UCLA and didn't do very well.
And here comes Bear Bryant.
And I basically knew about his Kentucky deal, but not that much.
But we were all excited.
And we all go to the Grove.
I remember it was at night and in the evening.
And he comes across, as I recall, from, at least I thought he did, maybe he'd been there earlier, but he came across from the little depot over there.
And he got up on that stage at the Grove, and he takes off his coat, and he takes off his tie, and he rolls up his sleeves, and he got up there and told us how it was going to be.
And I thought that was the greatest thing I ever saw.

and everybody responded oh yeah very very just went crazy uh and uh then that well we'd have yell practice and that you know well number one in those days we all had to make these uh signs on it was like big uh well there were like 10 by 20 sheets of
lightweight canvas kind of stuff.
And we would have to start making the sign immediately for the following week's game.
It was some kind of cartoon.
And I don't know how long they did that.
And it, you know, in some way degrade the opponent and show Sarge or whatever.
And those kind of cartoons, by the way, ran in all the major
dailies in those days.
They were famous for those cartoons.
And we'd start making them.
As soon as the game was over, we'd go back to the dorm and start making them.
And in theory, we were supposed to have them finished that night.
We'd take the old one down and you'd hang them from the very top of the building, get on the roof and hang it down.
And
But anyway, Yale practice.
And it wasn't held at midnight?
Oh, no.
It was held on Thursday, right after the evening chow.
Like, I don't know, 7, 7.30, something like that.
Then Saturday morning, what time did the routine begin for home game?
Well, usually in those days we played afternoon games.
I guess they started at 1 o'clock.
And the only thing I remember specifically was that of course we'd march into the game.
But you had morning classes.
all had Saturday morning classes, and couldn't wait to get out of those classes, going crazy over there.
And if your young lady came to town, you met her before the game.
Well, I never had that.
Oh, that didn't happen?
Okay.
It didn't happen to me.
So you marched in.
First sergeant collected.
You got those sheet of tickets when you registered.
You paid for all your athletes, and they'd collect your ticket, and then as we marched in, there'd be a ticket taker right there at that main gate to take all the tickets.
But, of course, they never counted them, and we always had a couple of friends from out of town in the middle of the ranks, you know, in some kind of uniform going in for free.
And we'd go around the horseshoe and then go up in the stands.
Now they come in two hours early, they leave, and then they come back.
Now do you remember at any football game during your time any great celebrity general reviewing the Corps?
Well, you know, I guess generals didn't impress me that much.
I don't remember.
I remember Alan Shivers being there.
Okay.
And I'm sure if I went back and looked at the annuals, there was some.
Eisenhower was president, and he had been at A&M earlier, but I don't think he came during that era.
I don't know of anybody.
Then during the game, did you and your buddies, were there any pranks or jokes or anything you remember?
No, we were just standing up and yelling.
We all had to sit down on the horseshoe as freshmen, and then you moved further up toward the 50-yard line as you went.

uh and then of course if we we won we went down there like they still do i guess get the the the l-eaters and and haul them off to prexy's pond do they still do that yes yes only the word prexy nobody uses anymore they don't no they don't know that they don't even know what that means you know the aggie land inn was there yeah yes uh wasn't still a comparatively nice place wasn't it
I never went inside of it.
The outside, you know, is kind of a Swiss chalet kind of thing.
Yeah, I think important visitors still stay there.
All right, then after the Aggies won a day game, if you and your buddies had a little extra money, what would you all have done on Saturday night?
Go to the movie.
Invariably went to the movie.
